                            <comment id="111235" author="haswellj" created="Thu, 8 Jan 2015 11:10:16 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve managed to work around this using BeanPostProcessors.  There&apos;s significantly more effort involved in this route, but there is a workaround.  I would like to leave this open as I feel like something along these lines would be valuable to the project, but I&apos;m dropping the priority to minor given that there is a workaround. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="111237" author="sbrannen" created="Thu, 8 Jan 2015 11:28:30 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Access the application context to register a Cluster configured from the annotation so that I may inject it into the test case.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Is the &lt;tt&gt;Cluster&lt;/tt&gt; intended to be injected into any Spring beans (other than just the test instance) managed by the &lt;tt&gt;ApplicationContext&lt;/tt&gt;?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If not, then there are certainly easier ways to achieve your goal... like invoking a method on or setting a field in the test instance (which you can access via the &lt;tt&gt;TestContext&lt;/tt&gt; in a &lt;tt&gt;TestExecutionListener&lt;/tt&gt;). In fact, people often define an interface (e.g., &lt;tt&gt;ClusterAwareTest&lt;/tt&gt; with a single &lt;tt&gt;setCluster(Cluster)&lt;/tt&gt; method) that test classes can implement, and a corresponding custom &lt;tt&gt;TestExecutionListener&lt;/tt&gt; that supports the interface and &lt;em&gt;injects&lt;/em&gt; the desired components without the need for the component to be registered in the Spring &lt;tt&gt;ApplicationContext&lt;/tt&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Would something like that be a more suitable solution for you?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="111238" author="sbrannen" created="Thu, 8 Jan 2015 11:31:23 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Would it be preferable to add an option to the TestExecutionListeners annotation to specify when the listeners would be applied? Or, more generally, would it be possible to modify the annotation such that you could configure when groups of listeners would be applied?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;No, the &lt;tt&gt;TestExecutionListener&lt;/tt&gt; API itself defines when callback methods must be invoked. Just see the names and documentation of each method in the &lt;tt&gt;TestExecutionListener&lt;/tt&gt; interface.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="111243" author="haswellj" created="Thu, 8 Jan 2015 12:00:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The cluster in this example is intended to be injected into every bean referencing a cluster, and so that approach doesn&apos;t quite work.  I could create the ClusterAware interface per your proposal and apply it to each bean, but I don&apos;t care much for this approach because, in a test environment, there are many configurations for clusters intended to test different aspects of interactions with a complex system.  For some tests, clusters are mocks.  For others, clusters are carefully-tuned production-level environments.  In deployment, every bean in a given application instance has access to the same cluster, and so I do not necessarily want to clutter the application with an artifact of testing.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A last alternative is to create different configurations for each type of cluster.  This also does about 95% of what I want it to do, but doesn&apos;t quite feel as nice, and I feel is more vulnerable to misuse by engineers.  &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Finally, it&apos;s not immediately clear from the documentation of &lt;tt&gt;TestExecutionListener&lt;/tt&gt; why you should not be able to apply a listener during a certain phase in the Spring wiring lifecycle.  The interface only specifies when each method is called relative to the test execution, except for the prepareTestInstance which is clearly called post-refresh.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="127920" author="sbrannen" created="Tue, 15 Mar 2016 19:29:14 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=haswellj&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;haswellj&quot;&gt;Josiah Haswell&lt;/a&gt;, you may be interested in the support recently introduced in conjunction with &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/browse/SPR-13998&quot; title=&quot;Introduce ContextCustomizer API in the TestContext framework&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SPR-13998&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SPR-13998&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &lt;tt&gt;ContextCustomizer&lt;/tt&gt; is similar to your proposed &lt;tt&gt;ContextDecorator&lt;/tt&gt;, but &lt;tt&gt;ContextCustomizer&lt;/tt&gt; is primarily targeted at third-party libraries (e.g., Spring Boot).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In any case, please let us know if &lt;tt&gt;ContextCustomizer&lt;/tt&gt; meets your needs.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
